name: Lampropeltis knoblochi Taylor, 1940
informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 29582m at the request of the observer
occurrenceRemarks: Adult male. W/C in 1982, between Yecora, Sonora and Creel, Chihuahua (note scarring between anterior blotches 19-22). Among the first individuals of this species imported into the US, these beautiful Mountain Kings are easily bred in captive situations, and have become a true "success story" in herpetoculture. One might even make the argument that there are possibly more captive-bred individuals of this species in the US and Europe than there are throughout their natural range! Truly a divergent form of "pyromelana", in comparison with their Southwestern US "conspecifics".

occurrenceRemarks: per SSAR (Crother et al 2017) Formerly considered a subspecies of L. pyromelana, Burbrink et al. (2011, Mol. Phylogenet. Evol. 60: 445–454) demonstrated the existence of two species using coalescent species delimitation methods and ecological niche modeling. The complex comprises a northern species on the Colorado Plateau (L. pyromelana) and a southern species (L. knoblochi) found primarily on the Sierra Madre Occidental and associated Madrean Sky Islands. 80 g 29.5 tb 831.2hpa 0 wind 30.1 c 25.1 rh

informationWithheld: Coordinate uncertainty increased to 29093m to protect threatened taxon
occurrenceRemarks: Originally identified as Arizona Mountain Kingsnake, but I was corrected that the ones in this location are genetically the Chihuahuan, and the morphology isn't a good indicator.
identificationRemarks: Technically this would be considered L. knoblochi under current taxonomy. This is the northernmost part of the range of L. knoblochi as outlined by Burbrink et al. 2011 (though they didn't actually sample from Mt. Lemmon or Mt. Graham, so I understand if people have quibbles with this area in particular). Great looking snake by either name.
